    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1814_10_10_page01.jpg"/>
                <!--filenames for photos associated with this letter. Example: <pb n="1" facs="image1.jpg image2.jpg image3.jpg"/> -->
                <opener>
                    <dateline><!--If there's no date line, omit this element. Record in the order in which it is written on the letter.-->
                        <name type="place" ref="EdgeworthsTown"/>Edgeworth's Town<lb/>
                        <date when="1814-10-10"/>October 10, 1814<lb/></dateline>
                    <salute> Dear Madam,<lb/>
                    </salute>
                </opener>
                <p> Inclosed I send a draft<lb/>
                    for ten pounds - Out of<lb/>
                    which I should be much<lb/>
                    obliged to you if you would<lb/>
                    pay <persName xml:id="FarrX1">>Miss Farrell</persName> the amount<lb/>
                    of her account enclosed and<lb/>
                    take a <hi rend="underline">settled</hi> at the bottom of<lb/>
                    her account - Give her also<lb/>
                    the enclosed note which I<lb/>
                    have written expressly to <choice><orig>re<lb/>
                        proach</orig><reg>reproach</reg></choice> her with sending the<lb/>
                    dresses in a box to <placeName>Ireland in</placeName><lb/>
                    stead of sending them to you as<lb/>
                    had been desired &amp; I have <choice><orig>request<lb/>
                        ed</orig><reg>requested</reg></choice>that she will never do so<lb/>
                    in the future.<lb/></p>
                <p> The balance of the ten pound<lb/>
                    Which will remain after<lb/>
                    <persName xml:id="FarrX1">Miss Farrell</persName> is paid I request<lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1814_10_10_page02.jpg"/>                      
                    My dear <persName xml:id="MileX1">Madam</persName> you will<lb/>
                    be so kind to keep in your<lb/>
                    hands to pay for any <choice><orig>commis<lb/>
                        sions</orig><reg>commissions</reg></choice>with which I may trouble<lb/>
                    you - Though <persName xml:id="Mile2">Mr. Miles</persName> is so<lb/>
                    very obliging to me, or rather<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">because</hi> he is so obliging to me<lb/>
                    I wish to avoid calling upon<lb/>
                    him &amp; plaguing him upon<lb/>
                    very trifling occasion. - I <choice><orig>in<lb/>
                        close</orig><reg>inclose</reg></choice>with many thanks a<lb/>
                    draft for the £2..14..0. which<lb/>
                    Line out of place<lb/>
                    he paid <persName xml:id="MoutX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Moutray</persName> for me<lb/></p>
                <p> I regret that he was not in<lb/>
                    the way when <persName xml:id="MoutX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Moutray</persName> &amp;<lb/>
                    her daughter called as they<lb/>
                    are two of the most amiable<lb/>
                    &amp; charming of our friends, whom<lb/>
                    I should have been proud that<lb/>
                <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1814_10_10_page03.jpg"/>                   
                    he should have seen &amp; whom<lb/>
                    I am sure he would have been<lb/>
                    pleased to see<lb/></p>
                <p> Quite at your leisure when<lb/>
                    you are looking for any thing<lb/>
                    at a haberdashers for yourself<lb/>
                    will you get for me 6 yards<lb/>
                    of ribbon same as the pattern<lb/>
                    of ribbon which you bought<lb/>
                    for me - If the color matches<lb/>
                    I do not mind what the pattern<lb/>
                    may be as I want it for sashes<lb/>
                    for my <unclear>sasnet</unclear> gown of this color<lb/></p>
                <p> I rejoice to hear that you<lb/>
                    like the continuation of <title xml:id="w4">Early Lessons</title><lb/>
                    the most agreeable compliments<lb/>
                    we ever have or ever shall receive<lb/>
                    are those which we are sometimes<lb/>
                    so fortunate to hear from really<lb/>
                    good mothers who are interestd<lb/>
                    upon the education of their children<lb/></p>
                <p> Pray if the <title><hi rend="underline">Robins petition</hi></title> or the<lb/>
                    songs in the <title><hi rend="underline">Knapsack</hi></title> have been set to<lb/>
                    music make <persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName> sent them to<lb/>
                    me as a Christmas box for one of my<lb/>
                    little sisters <persName xml:id="RuxtS1">(Sophy)</persName> who has an agreeable<lb/>
                    voice &amp; will take pleasure &amp; pride in<lb/>
                    singing them to my <persName xml:id="EdgeR1">father</persName><lb/></p>
                <closer> 
                    I am dear Madam<lb/>
                    Sincerely yours<lb/>
                    <persName xml:id="EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                    Excuse my mistake<lb/>
                        in tearing this paper<lb/>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Beinecke_330_1814_10_10_page04.jpg"/>
                    <p><persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName><lb/>
                    I will further trouble you to<lb/>
                    buy for me a dozen gilt <hi rend="underline">clothes</hi><lb/>
                    such as are used for bracelets or<lb/>
                    any kind that will fasten a cloth<lb/>
                    pelisse - they will not be seen as<lb/>
                    they will fasten it within side<lb/>
                    so that I shall think more of the<lb/>
                    goodness of the <hi rend="underline">catch</hi> than of the beauty<lb/>
                    - <persName xml:id="MileX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Miles</persName> will soon send a packet<lb/>
                    under a government frank but<lb/>
                    do <hi rend="underline">not</hi> send them in that because I<lb/>
                    have promised not to do so - wait till<lb/>
                    some member of parliament can frank<lb/>
                    them - they will come safely between<lb/>
                        two cards in one or two common franks<lb/></p>
                </postscript>
                <!--You can include a <pb/> here, or inside the postScript.-->
